[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":668},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F13\u002Fjs-from-zero-28-es6-loops\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F13\u002Fjs-from-zero-28-es6-loops\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F13\u002Fjs-from-zero-28-es6-loops\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F13\u002Fjs-from-zero-28-es6-loops\u002F":643,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F10\u002F13\u002Fjs-from-zero-28-es6-loops\u002F":652},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20191013\u002F1749328948\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":626,"date":627,"description":628,"extension":629,"lang":630,"meta":631,"navigation":123,"path":632,"readingMinutes":633,"seo":634,"standalone":635,"stem":636,"tags":637,"tldr":640,"updated":627,"url":641,"__hash__":642},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-from-zero-28-es6-loops.md","Learning JS From Zero, Day 28: ES6 Loops With forEach and for...of","1002185647",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":620},"minimark",[11,16,29,32,39,46,52,177,180,186,189,307,310,315,318,423,426,484,487,493,496,499,505,510,513,574,593,602,609,613,616],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19,20,24,25,28],"p",{},"Day 28 of getting reincarnated into JavaScript. This time I'm going to cover two ES6 ways to loop: ",[21,22,23],"code",{},"forEach"," and ",[21,26,27],{},"for...of",".",[12,30,23],{"id":31},"foreach",[17,33,34,35,38],{},"ES6 simplified a lot of everyday dev stuff, and looping is no exception. With a classic ",[21,36,37],{},"for"," loop you'd normally write something like this ↓",[17,40,41],{},[42,43],"img",{"alt":44,"src":45},"for loop definition","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FKwtkev8.png",[17,47,48,49,51],{},"So if you wanted to loop over an array with a ",[21,50,37],{}," loop, you'd have to write it like this:",[53,54,59],"pre",{"className":55,"code":56,"language":57,"meta":58,"style":58},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var arrayData = ['a', 'b', 'c'];\nvar len = arrayData.length;\n\nfor(var i = 0; i \u003C len;i++) {\n  console.log(arrayData[i]);\n}\n","js","",[21,60,61,98,118,125,158,171],{"__ignoreMap":58},[62,63,66,70,74,77,80,84,87,90,92,95],"span",{"class":64,"line":65},"line",1,[62,67,69],{"class":68},"sWyjQ","var",[62,71,73],{"class":72},"sMAXC"," arrayData ",[62,75,76],{"class":68},"=",[62,78,79],{"class":72}," [",[62,81,83],{"class":82},"sTRMh","'a'",[62,85,86],{"class":72},", ",[62,88,89],{"class":82},"'b'",[62,91,86],{"class":72},[62,93,94],{"class":82},"'c'",[62,96,97],{"class":72},"];\n",[62,99,101,103,106,108,111,115],{"class":64,"line":100},2,[62,102,69],{"class":68},[62,104,105],{"class":72}," len ",[62,107,76],{"class":68},[62,109,110],{"class":72}," arrayData.",[62,112,114],{"class":113},"sCcAr","length",[62,116,117],{"class":72},";\n",[62,119,121],{"class":64,"line":120},3,[62,122,124],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":123},true,"\n",[62,126,128,130,133,135,138,140,143,146,149,152,155],{"class":64,"line":127},4,[62,129,37],{"class":68},[62,131,132],{"class":72},"(",[62,134,69],{"class":68},[62,136,137],{"class":72}," i ",[62,139,76],{"class":68},[62,141,142],{"class":113}," 0",[62,144,145],{"class":72},"; i ",[62,147,148],{"class":68},"\u003C",[62,150,151],{"class":72}," len;i",[62,153,154],{"class":68},"++",[62,156,157],{"class":72},") {\n",[62,159,161,164,168],{"class":64,"line":160},5,[62,162,163],{"class":72},"  console.",[62,165,167],{"class":166},"sj_SG","log",[62,169,170],{"class":72},"(arrayData[i]);\n",[62,172,174],{"class":64,"line":173},6,[62,175,176],{"class":72},"}\n",[17,178,179],{},"Honestly, just typing out everything inside those parentheses already feels like a chore, and on top of that you have to declare a separate variable to hold the array length. But with the new ES6 syntax? It saves you a ton of hassle. Here's how it's structured ↓",[17,181,182],{},[42,183],{"alt":184,"src":185},"forEach definition","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FaoJ97Dm.png",[17,187,188],{},"So we can rewrite it like this:",[53,190,192],{"className":55,"code":191,"language":57,"meta":58,"style":58},"var arrayData = ['a', 'b', 'c'];\n\narrayData.forEach(function(item,index,array){\n  console.log('value' + item);\n  console.log('index' + index);\n  console.log('the array itself' + array);\n})\n",[21,193,194,216,220,252,269,285,301],{"__ignoreMap":58},[62,195,196,198,200,202,204,206,208,210,212,214],{"class":64,"line":65},[62,197,69],{"class":68},[62,199,73],{"class":72},[62,201,76],{"class":68},[62,203,79],{"class":72},[62,205,83],{"class":82},[62,207,86],{"class":72},[62,209,89],{"class":82},[62,211,86],{"class":72},[62,213,94],{"class":82},[62,215,97],{"class":72},[62,217,218],{"class":64,"line":100},[62,219,124],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":123},[62,221,222,225,227,229,232,234,238,241,244,246,249],{"class":64,"line":120},[62,223,224],{"class":72},"arrayData.",[62,226,23],{"class":166},[62,228,132],{"class":72},[62,230,231],{"class":68},"function",[62,233,132],{"class":72},[62,235,237],{"class":236},"s_sBn","item",[62,239,240],{"class":72},",",[62,242,243],{"class":236},"index",[62,245,240],{"class":72},[62,247,248],{"class":236},"array",[62,250,251],{"class":72},"){\n",[62,253,254,256,258,260,263,266],{"class":64,"line":127},[62,255,163],{"class":72},[62,257,167],{"class":166},[62,259,132],{"class":72},[62,261,262],{"class":82},"'value'",[62,264,265],{"class":68}," +",[62,267,268],{"class":72}," item);\n",[62,270,271,273,275,277,280,282],{"class":64,"line":160},[62,272,163],{"class":72},[62,274,167],{"class":166},[62,276,132],{"class":72},[62,278,279],{"class":82},"'index'",[62,281,265],{"class":68},[62,283,284],{"class":72}," index);\n",[62,286,287,289,291,293,296,298],{"class":64,"line":173},[62,288,163],{"class":72},[62,290,167],{"class":166},[62,292,132],{"class":72},[62,294,295],{"class":82},"'the array itself'",[62,297,265],{"class":68},[62,299,300],{"class":72}," array);\n",[62,302,304],{"class":64,"line":303},7,[62,305,306],{"class":72},"})\n",[17,308,309],{},"You can see the loop syntax is way shorter, and a lot easier to write ↓",[17,311,312],{},[42,313],{"alt":23,"src":314},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FZj4Jnu7.png",[17,316,317],{},"And of course you can make it even shorter. We learned arrow functions earlier, so you can write it like this:",[53,319,321],{"className":55,"code":320,"language":57,"meta":58,"style":58},"var arrayData = ['a', 'b', 'c'];\n\narrayData.forEach((item,index,array) => {\n  console.log('value' + item);\n  console.log('index' + index);\n  console.log('the array itself' + array);\n})\n",[21,322,323,345,349,377,391,405,419],{"__ignoreMap":58},[62,324,325,327,329,331,333,335,337,339,341,343],{"class":64,"line":65},[62,326,69],{"class":68},[62,328,73],{"class":72},[62,330,76],{"class":68},[62,332,79],{"class":72},[62,334,83],{"class":82},[62,336,86],{"class":72},[62,338,89],{"class":82},[62,340,86],{"class":72},[62,342,94],{"class":82},[62,344,97],{"class":72},[62,346,347],{"class":64,"line":100},[62,348,124],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":123},[62,350,351,353,355,358,360,362,364,366,368,371,374],{"class":64,"line":120},[62,352,224],{"class":72},[62,354,23],{"class":166},[62,356,357],{"class":72},"((",[62,359,237],{"class":236},[62,361,240],{"class":72},[62,363,243],{"class":236},[62,365,240],{"class":72},[62,367,248],{"class":236},[62,369,370],{"class":72},") ",[62,372,373],{"class":68},"=>",[62,375,376],{"class":72}," {\n",[62,378,379,381,383,385,387,389],{"class":64,"line":127},[62,380,163],{"class":72},[62,382,167],{"class":166},[62,384,132],{"class":72},[62,386,262],{"class":82},[62,388,265],{"class":68},[62,390,268],{"class":72},[62,392,393,395,397,399,401,403],{"class":64,"line":160},[62,394,163],{"class":72},[62,396,167],{"class":166},[62,398,132],{"class":72},[62,400,279],{"class":82},[62,402,265],{"class":68},[62,404,284],{"class":72},[62,406,407,409,411,413,415,417],{"class":64,"line":173},[62,408,163],{"class":72},[62,410,167],{"class":166},[62,412,132],{"class":72},[62,414,295],{"class":82},[62,416,265],{"class":68},[62,418,300],{"class":72},[62,420,421],{"class":64,"line":303},[62,422,306],{"class":72},[17,424,425],{},"If the body is just a single line of output, you can shorten it even more:",[53,427,429],{"className":55,"code":428,"language":57,"meta":58,"style":58},"var arrayData = ['a', 'b', 'c'];\n\narrayData.forEach(item => console.log('value' + item))\n",[21,430,431,453,457],{"__ignoreMap":58},[62,432,433,435,437,439,441,443,445,447,449,451],{"class":64,"line":65},[62,434,69],{"class":68},[62,436,73],{"class":72},[62,438,76],{"class":68},[62,440,79],{"class":72},[62,442,83],{"class":82},[62,444,86],{"class":72},[62,446,89],{"class":82},[62,448,86],{"class":72},[62,450,94],{"class":82},[62,452,97],{"class":72},[62,454,455],{"class":64,"line":100},[62,456,124],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":123},[62,458,459,461,463,465,467,470,473,475,477,479,481],{"class":64,"line":120},[62,460,224],{"class":72},[62,462,23],{"class":166},[62,464,132],{"class":72},[62,466,237],{"class":236},[62,468,469],{"class":68}," =>",[62,471,472],{"class":72}," console.",[62,474,167],{"class":166},[62,476,132],{"class":72},[62,478,262],{"class":82},[62,480,265],{"class":68},[62,482,483],{"class":72}," item))\n",[17,485,486],{},"And it runs perfectly fine ↓",[17,488,489],{},[42,490],{"alt":491,"src":492},"one-liner","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FFNJ6rZR.png",[17,494,495],{},"This compact form is also known as shorthand syntax.",[12,497,27],{"id":498},"forof",[17,500,501,502,504],{},"Next up is another way to loop over arrays. This one I personally use a bit less often — it's ",[21,503,27],{},", and it's also really simple to write ↓",[17,506,507],{},[42,508],{"alt":27,"src":509},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002Fqm2ebg7.png",[17,511,512],{},"So we can rewrite the earlier example like this:",[53,514,516],{"className":55,"code":515,"language":57,"meta":58,"style":58},"var arrayData = ['a', 'b', 'c'];\n\nfor(var item of arrayData) {\n  console.log(item);\n}\n",[21,517,518,540,544,561,570],{"__ignoreMap":58},[62,519,520,522,524,526,528,530,532,534,536,538],{"class":64,"line":65},[62,521,69],{"class":68},[62,523,73],{"class":72},[62,525,76],{"class":68},[62,527,79],{"class":72},[62,529,83],{"class":82},[62,531,86],{"class":72},[62,533,89],{"class":82},[62,535,86],{"class":72},[62,537,94],{"class":82},[62,539,97],{"class":72},[62,541,542],{"class":64,"line":100},[62,543,124],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":123},[62,545,546,548,550,552,555,558],{"class":64,"line":120},[62,547,37],{"class":68},[62,549,132],{"class":72},[62,551,69],{"class":68},[62,553,554],{"class":72}," item ",[62,556,557],{"class":68},"of",[62,559,560],{"class":72}," arrayData) {\n",[62,562,563,565,567],{"class":64,"line":127},[62,564,163],{"class":72},[62,566,167],{"class":166},[62,568,569],{"class":72},"(item);\n",[62,571,572],{"class":64,"line":160},[62,573,176],{"class":72},[17,575,576,577,580,581,583,584,586,587,589,590,592],{},"People sometimes compare ES5's ",[21,578,579],{},"for...in"," with ES6's ",[21,582,27],{},". Basically, the way I personally split it: I use ",[21,585,579],{}," mostly for object data, and ",[21,588,27],{}," for arrays. Dividing them up by purpose like that makes them easier to keep straight. ",[21,591,579],{}," is really meant for objects, so the two are genuinely a bit different.",[17,594,595,596,28],{},"For the details, check out MDN's writeup on ",[597,598,579],"a",{"href":599,"rel":600},"https:\u002F\u002Fdeveloper.mozilla.org\u002Fen-US\u002Fdocs\u002FWeb\u002FJavaScript\u002FReference\u002FStatements\u002Ffor...in",[601],"nofollow",[17,603,604,605,28],{},"And finally, if you're curious about the other ways to work with arrays, take a look at this earlier post of mine: ",[597,606,608],{"href":607},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20190421\u002F1216566123\u002F","20 ways to work with JavaScript arrays (article in Mandarin)",[12,610,612],{"id":611},"wrapping-up","Wrapping up",[17